content: Today, the topic is the exciting variant of d12/d5 opening, invented by Russian players,
and which was even analysed by some students here before the lesson.
To go back to history of this variant,
it appeared in top level tournaments in summer 2005, during World Championship AT.
whenever d5 or d12 is opened, the opponent swaps almost every time,
whereas white has won nearly all games with this 8th move.
dongfujia says, its a very good move.
I am not as smart as he is
so I will not rush with this conclusion
In my mind, a deep analysis is needed, to realize, either it is good for white or black.
Even the authors of the variant (Sushkov and Chingin) are not so sure yet
i see long positional war from now
the 8th move appeared in the 7th round in game Karlsson-Sushkov,
Both games were won by white, after long fight.
But it became quite evident, that white got the initiative fast,
Let me briefly show those games first, at least the beginnings.
Karlsson-Sushkov, a passive 9th move by Stefan.
But surprisingly he was able to get still a quite competitive position.
So white is force to break the 3x3 situation at d7.
After 21st move, the position became very chaotic.
Perhaps this 29th move was the moment,
when white completely got the initiative.
After that the game went on with white's increasing advantage,
and by the 56th move, white had won.
this is the full record of that game.
maybe if black would be more active here,
perhaps it would be possible to develop something first.
whether white has VCT on the left side or not.
who will be white now, say me
and you can try white's attack.
its just an analysis, not exam.
Don't be afraid to try, even I dont know yet, whether its win or not.

Anyway, it seems that the active 9th moves are at risk of losing,
so maybe such peaceful 9th move is a good way.
But there will be a question -
if the 9th move gives less advantage for black than the other 5th move (5-i8),
then maybe it is wiser for black to use 5-i8 for a while,
until a sufficient plan for black is found here.
And now, we will end the lesson! Thanks to all the active students today, who used the board to show their moves, well done!
